    <section class="section-static">
        <h2>Static Positioning (Default)</h2>
        <p>This section uses static positioning, which is the default. It flows naturally in the document without any special positioning applied.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Relative Positioning -->
    <section class="section-relative">
        <h2>Relative Positioning</h2>
        <p>This section is relatively positioned. Inside, there's a box that is moved 30px to the right and 20px down using <code>left</code> and <code>top</code> with <code>position: relative</code>.</p>
        <div class="relative-box">
            I am relatively positioned.
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Absolute Positioning -->
    <section class="section-absolute">
        <h2>Absolute Positioning</h2>
        <p>This section is relatively positioned, but inside it, there's an absolutely positioned box that ignores the normal flow and is placed 50px from the top and 50px from the left.</p>
        <div class="absolute-box">
            I am absolutely positioned inside a relative container.
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Fixed Positioning -->
    <section class="section-fixed">
        <h2>Fixed Positioning</h2>
        <p>This section demonstrates fixed positioning. The box below is always fixed at the bottom-right corner of the page, even when you scroll.</p>
        <div class="fixed-box">
            I stay fixed at the bottom right!
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Sticky Positioning -->
    <section class="section-sticky">
        <h2>Sticky Positioning</h2>
        <div class="sticky-header">
            I stick to the top when you scroll!
        </div>
        <div class="sticky-content">
            <p>Scroll down to see the sticky effect in action. The header will stick to the top when you reach it while scrolling inside this section.</p>
            <p>Sticky positioning combines the behavior of relative and fixed positioning. When you scroll, the element stays relative until it reaches a defined point, then it becomes fixed at that point.</p>
            <p>Keep scrolling to see more content here, and watch how the sticky header works!</p>
            <p>This section is tall enough to demonstrate the sticky effect, allowing the header to stick to the top once you scroll past a certain point.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

